<chapter xml:id="CHAPTERApplicaitonsOfIntegration" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Integration Techniques</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      The easiest way to compute an integral is to simply know what it
      is in the first place; to have it memorized.  For example, entry
      #8 of <xref
      ref="TABLEBasicIntegration"></xref> tells us that,
      <m>\int\cos(x){\dx{x} = \sin(x)+C }</m>.  But with a little
      cleverness we can use it to evaluate other integrals as
      well.  <q>Cleverness</q>  comes in may forms but as we<rsq/>ve
      seen one of the simplest ways to be clever is to make our
      formulas <q>easier on the eyes</q> by making a substitution. 
    </p>
    <problem xml:id="DRILLVerySimpleSubst">
      <p>
        For example, use the substitution <m>y=5x</m> to show that
        <me>\int \cos(5x) \dx{x} = \frac15\sin(5x)+C </me>.
      </p>
    </problem>

    <p>
      In fact substitution is by far the most powerful means we have
      of computing integrals. But simply computing integrals for
      it<rsq/>s own sake, while fun, is a little sterile. We are not
      here to simply grind out computations, that<rsq/>s what machines
      are for. Our interest is in understanding and explaining the
      natural world. In the next section we<rsq/>ll see how we can use
      the notion of an integral to extend <xref
      ref="SECTIONGalileoDrops" text="custom">Galileo<rsq/>s work </xref>  on
      falling bodies.
    </p>


  </introduction>

  <section  xml:id="SECTIONSubstMethed">
