<subsection xml:id="SUBSECTIONTrigSubst">
  <title> Trigonometric (Inverse) Substitutions</title>

  <p>
    Recall that when we were trying to determine the solution to the
    catenary in <xref ref="EXAMPLEHardDiffeq"></xref> we encountered
    the integral
    <me>
      \int{\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z} }
    </me>
    which we didn<rsq/>t (and still don<rsq/>t) know how to do. This
    integral can be computed using a substitution also, but the
    substitution to use here is <q>backwards</q> compared to the ones
    we used in <xref ref="SUBSECTIONSimpleSubstitution"></xref>. This
    sort of substitution comes up frequently when the integrand
    involves trigonometric functions so it is often called
    <term>Trigonometric</term>  or <term>Inverse Substitution</term>.
  </p>
  <p>
    The
    substitution we need is <m>z=\tan{\theta } </m>. We will come back
    and address how we might have guessed this once we have finished
    computing the integral. For now, do you see why we said this is
    <q>backwards?</q> 
  </p>

  <p>
    Previously, we have set the substitution variable (usually
    <m>u</m>) to be some expression in the integration variable
    (usually <m>x</m>). This usually makes the integrand simpler. For
    example, given <m>\int \cos(2x){\dx{x}}</m> we<rsq/>d let
    <m>u=2x</m>.

  </p>
  <p>
    But    if we let <m>z=\tan{\theta }</m>, then
    <m>\dx{\theta{}}=\sec^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}</m>, and so we have


    <me>      \int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}=
    \int\frac{\sec^2(\theta )}
    {\sqrt{1+\tan^2(\theta)}}\dx{\theta}</me>
    which seems to be considerably more complicated than the original
    problem. 
  </p>
  <aside>
    <title>Comment</title>
    <p>
      A former teacher of one of the authors was fond of saying
      <q>Why simplify when you can complicate?</q> in this situation.
    </p>
  </aside>
  <p>
    But remember that our goal is not to make the integral
    simpler. Our goal is to make the integral doable. In this case
    observe that <men xml:id="EQUATIONPythTrigSecTan">\sec^2( \theta ) = 1+\tan^2 (\theta )</men> so we
    see that  
    <md>
      <mrow>\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}\amp{}      =
      \int\frac{\sec^2(\theta)}{\sec(\theta)}\dx{\theta}</mrow>
      <mrow> \amp{}     =\int\sec(\theta)\dx{\theta}
      </mrow>
      <mrow>\amp{}      =\ln\abs{\tan(\theta)+\sec(\theta)}+c
      </mrow>

    </md>
  </p>
  <p>
    The trick now is to put everything back in terms of <m>z</m>.  We
    have <m>\tan(\theta)=z</m> from our substitution, but what about
    <m>\sec(\theta)</m>?  We could certainly use the trigonometric
    identity in <xref ref="EQUATIONPythTrigSecTan">equation</xref>,
    but it is often simpler to draw an appropriate triangle. 
  </p>
  <p>
    The appropriate triangle in this case is the one with <m>\theta
    </m> in standard position. The beauty of this is that we
    don<rsq/>t need to know what the angle <m>\theta{}</m> is.  All we
    need to know is that <m>\tan(\theta)=\frac{z}{1}</m>. Since in a
    right triangle <m>\tan( \theta ) =
    \frac{\text{opposite}}{\text{adjacent}}</m> we have this triangle:
  </p>
  <figure>
    <caption>Diagram of a right triangle  where <m>\tan (\theta ) =z</m></caption>
    <image source="IC/zeqtan.png" width="40%">
      <shortdescription>Diagram of a right
      triangle.</shortdescription>
    </image>
  </figure>



  <p>
    Notice that since we<rsq/>ve got two sides of a right triangle we
    can compute the third side as shown.  And knowing the length of
    all three sides of a right triangle allows us to compute all of
    the trigonometic functions of <m>\theta </m> triangle, not only can we obtain the aforementioned
    <m>\tan(\theta)=\frac{z}{1}=z</m> and
    <m>\sec(\theta)=\frac{\sqrt{1+z^2}}{1}</m>. These are the two
    formulas  we
    need for this problem, but we could also obtain the formulas 
    <md>
      <mrow>\sin(\theta)\amp =\frac{z}{\sqrt{1+z^2}},\amp{}\cos(\theta)\amp =\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}},</mrow>
      <mrow>\cot(\theta)\amp =\frac1z,\amp{}\csc(\theta)\amp =\frac{\sqrt{1+z^2}}{z}.</mrow>
    </md>
    if we needed them.
  </p>
  <p>
    We really urge you to do this (DRAW A TRIANGLE) instead of
    relying on memorizing trigonometric identities which actually
    are derived from the triangle. This gives us that the
    differential equation
    <me>
      \int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}=\int\frac{w}{H}\dx{x}
    </me>
    is satisfied by
    <me>
      \ln\left(z+\sqrt{1+z^2}\right)=\frac{w}{H}x+c.
    </me>
  </p>
  <exercise>
    



    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the formula <m>z=\dfdx{y}{x}</m> for the catenary and
          <m>z(0)=\dfdx{y}{x}{0}=0</m> (this was the low
          point on the hanging chain) to show that <m>c=0</m> and
          so
          <me>
            \dfdx{y}{x}=z=\frac12\left(e^{\frac{w}{H}x}-e^{-\frac{w}{H}x}\right).
          </me>
        </p>
        <aside>
          <title>Note to self</title>
          <p>The use of <m>y</m> and <m>z</m> interchangeably is
