  <p>
    Consider the top view of an airplane <m>P</m> starting at the
    point <m>(1,0)</m> and traveling up the line <m> x=1</m> at a
    constant speed <m>v</m>.  When the plane is at <m>(1,0)</m>, a
    homing missile <m>M</m> is fired from the origin directly at
    the plane. Assuming that the missile travels at a speed which
    is <m>k</m> times the speed of the plane <m>(k>1)</m> and is
    always aimed directly at the plane, find the path the missile
    takes.  [Such a path is called a pursuit curve.]  The diagram
    below shows the situation at time <m>t</m>.
  </p>
  <figure>
    <caption>
      Image of a pursuit curve.
    </caption>
    <image source="IC/PursuitCurve.png" width="75%">
      <shortdescription>
        Image of a pursuit curve.
      </shortdescription>
    </image>
  </figure>

  <exercise xml:id="PursuitCurve1">
    
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If we let <m>s</m> denote the distance the missile has
          traveled at time <m>t</m>, show that the missile's path
          must satisfy the IVP

          <mdn>
            <mrow xml:id="PursuitEquation1">
              \dfdx{y}{x}=\frac{\frac{s}{k}-y}{1-x},\amp{}\amp{}
              y(0)=0.
            </mrow>
          </mdn>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Obviously we can solve <xref
          ref="PursuitEquation1">equation</xref> for <m>y</m> but
          then we would have <m>y</m> in terms of <m>x</m>,
          <m>s</m>, and <m>\dfdx{y}{x}</m> which isn't very
          helpful. The <m>s</m> term is particularly problematic
          since we know almost nothing about it.
        </p>
        <p>
          But only almost. We do know that
          <m>\dx{s}^2=\dx{x}^2+\dx{y}^2</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Differentiate <xref
          ref="PursuitEquation1">equation</xref> to show that the
          missile<rsq/>s path must satisfy the differential equation
          <md>
            <mrow>(1-x)\dfdxn{y}{x}{2}=\frac{1}{k}\dfdx{s}{x}=\frac1k\sqrt{1+\left(\dfdx{y}{x}\right)^2{}}</mrow>
          </md>
          with the initial conditions <m>y(0)=0</m>, and
          <m>\dfdxat{y}{x}{0}=0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let's make this a little easier on our eyes. Let
          <m>z=\dfdx{y}{x} </m>, and show that <xref
          ref="PursuitEquation1">equation</xref> becomes
          <men xml:id="PursuitEquation2">
            \frac{1}{\sqrt{1+z^2}}\dx{z}=\frac1k\cdot\frac{1}{1-x}
          </men>
          with initial conditions <m>z(0)=0</m>.  and use the
          trigonometric substitution <m>z=\tan(\theta)</m> as
          before to show that
          <me>
            z=\frac12\left(\left(1-x\right)^{\frac{-1}{k}}-\left(1-x\right)^{\frac1k}\right){}
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the initial condition <m>y(0)=0</m> and the
          substitution <m>z=\dfdx{y}{x}</m> to show that
          <me>
            y=\frac{k}{2}\left[\frac{(1-x)^{\frac{k+1}{k}}}{k+1}+\frac{(1-x)^{\frac{k-1}{k}}}{k-1}\right]+\frac{k}{k^2-1}
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          How far has the plane gone when the missile reaches it?
          What happens as <m>x\rightarrow1</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <p>
    Of course, the tangent function is not the only trigonometric
    function at our disposal.
  </p>



  <exercise xml:id="TractrixProblem1">
    

