      <!--       <cell><m>\dx(\inverse\sin(x))= -->
      <!--       \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\dx{x}</m></cell> -->
      <!--       <cell><m>\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\dx{x}=\inverse\sin(x)+c</m></cell> -->
      <!--     </row> -->
      <!--     <row> -->
      <!--       <cell><m>\dx(\inverse\tan(x))= -->
      <!--       \frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x}</m></cell> -->
      <!--       <cell><m>\int\frac{1}{1+x^2}\dx{x}=\inverse\tan(x)+c</m></cell> -->
      <!--     </row> -->
      <!--     <row> -->
      <!--       <cell><m>\dx(\inverse\sec(x))= -->
      <!--       \frac{1}{x\sqrt{x^2-1}}\dx{x}</m></cell> -->
      <!--       <cell><m>\int\frac{1}{x\sqrt{x^2-1}}\dx{x}=\inverse\sec(x)+c</m></cell> -->
      <!--     </row> -->
      <!--   </tabular> -->
      <!-- </table> -->
      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   You can memorize it if you like, but if you for get one of -->
      <!--   these formulas they are straightforward to derive. -->
      <!-- </p> -->
      <p>        This problems asks you to verify Integration Rules <xref
      ref="IntRuleInvSin"></xref>, <xref
      ref="IntRuleInvTan"></xref>, and <xref
      ref="IntRuleInvSec"></xref>, directly. 
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the substitution <m>x=\sin(\theta)</m> to compute
          <m>\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\dx{x}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the substitution <m>x=\tan(\theta)</m> to compute
          <m>\int{\frac{1}{1+x^2}}\dx{x}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the substitution <m>x=\sec(\theta)</m> to compute
          <m>\int\frac{1}{x\sqrt{x^2-1}}\dx{x}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <p>
    This is all well and good, but the forms <m>\sqrt{1-x^2}</m>,
    <m>\sqrt{1+x^2}</m>, and <m>\sqrt{x^2-1}</m> are all very
    specific. Can we use them for an integral like
    <m>
      \int\frac{1}{\sqrt{4+x^2}}\dx{x} </m>?
  </p>
  <p>
    Of course we can. We just need to rearrange it using Algebra.
    Observe that if we had a <m>1</m> where the <m>4</m> is we<rsq/>d be
    fine. We can't just change it. That would change the entire
    integral. But if we factor  out the <m>4</m> we get
    <men xml:id="TrigSubst1">
      \int\frac{1}{\sqrt{4+x^2}}\dx{x}=\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{4\left(1+\frac{x^2}{4}\right)}}\dx{x}=\frac12\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)^2}}\dx{x}
    </men>
  </p>
  <p>
    Of course, now we have another problem. We have
    <m>\left(\frac{x}{2}\right)^2</m> where we were happy to have
    <m>x^2</m> before. But since we were going to substitute
    <m>x</m> away anyhow we'll just substitute <m>\frac{x}{2}</m>
    away instead.
  </p>
  <p>
    Letting <m>\frac{x}{2}=\tan(\theta)</m>, we proceed as before.
  </p>

  <exercise xml:id="TrigSubst2">
    

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Finish computing the integral in <xref
          ref="TrigSubst1">equation</xref>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute <m>\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{5-x^2}}\dx{x}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute <m>\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2-9}}\dx{x}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute <m>\int\frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2-6x}}\dx{x}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          This integral appears to be a completely different from
          the others in this problem, but it
          really isn't. Complete the square on <m>x^2-6x</m> and
          then use your result in part (c).
        </p>
      </hint>
    </task>
  </exercise>
  <p>
    It should be clear from <xref ref="TrigSubst2"></xref>
    that as long as the expression inside the radical is a
    quadratic, we can manipulate it algebraically to produce
    something of the form
    <m>\sqrt{1+\left(\frac{x-b}{a}\right)^2}</m>,
    <m>\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{x-b}{a}\right)^2}</m>or
    <m>\sqrt{\left(\frac{x-b}{a}\right)^2-1}</m>.  From there, we
    can use the appropriate trigonometric substitution.
  </p>

  <p>
    Earlier we computed terminal velocity when considering linear
    drag. Now we will compare this to terminal velocity when the
    drag is proportional to the square of the velocity. An example
    of this would be a ball of mass <m>M</m> falling in air. (We
    can include buoyancy again, but it is typically negligible so
    we will discount it). Again, to model this, let<m>y(t)</m> be
    distance the ball has fallen (so the positive <m>y</m> axis is
    pointing downward), with <m>y(0)=0</m> representing the initial
    position of the ball. In a similar analysis to before, we
    denote the acceleration due to gravity by <m>g</m>, so the
    weight of the ball is <m>Mg</m>. The drag, which we assume is
    now quadratic, is proportional to the square of the velocity,
    so we will denote this by <m>-Rv^2</m>, where <m>R</m> is a
    constant and <m>v=\dfdx{v}{t}</m> is the velocity. For
    simplicity, we will assume <m>v(0)=0</m>.
  </p>

  <exercise xml:id="FallingWithDrag">
    


    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use Newton's Second Law of Motion:
          (<m>F</m>)<m>=</m>(<m>M</m>)ass<m>\cdot{}</m>(<m>A</m>)cceleration,
          to show that the velocity of the ball must satisfy the
          equations:
          <me>
            M\dfdx{v}{t}=Mg-Rv^2, \hskip5mm{}v(0)=0 </me>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Show that the IVP above is equivalent to
          <me>
            \frac{\dx{v}}{1-\frac{R}{Mg}v^2}=g\dx{t}, \hskip5mm
            v(0)=0 </me>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the substitution <m>\sqrt{\frac{R}{Mg}}v =
          \sin(\theta)</m> to show that 
          
          <me>
            v=\sqrt{\frac{Mg}{R}}\left[\frac{1-e^{-2gt}}{1+e^{-2gt}}\right]                      </me>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute <m>\limit{t}{\infty}{v}</m>. Compare this
          terminal velocity with our previous results.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

  </exercise>

  <p>
    The trigonometric substitutions we've dealt with so far have
    all involved square roots. What about this integral:
    <m>\int\frac{\dx{x}}{(1-x^2)^\frac32}</m>? Do you see that this
    is only slightly more complicated?
  </p>
  <p>
    If we make the substitution <m>x=\sin(\theta)</m>, then
    <m>\dx{x}=\cos(\theta)</m> as before so,
    <me>
      \int\frac{\dx{x}}{(1-x^2)^\frac32} =
      \int\frac{\cos(\theta)}{\left(\sqrt{1-\sin^2(\theta)}\right)^3}\dx{\theta}=\int\frac{\cos(\theta)}{\cos^3(\theta)}\dx{\theta}=\int\sec^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}=\tan(\theta)+c
      </me>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Since <m>\sin(\theta)=\frac{x}{2}</m>, we get the triangle
  </p>
  <figure>
    <caption>Image of the triangle</caption>
    <image source="IC/TrigTri1.png" width="40%">
      <shortdescription>Image of the triangle with theta in
      standard position and legs x and square root of one - x
      squared.</shortdescription>
    </image>
  </figure>
  <p>
    so
    <me>
      \int\frac{\dx{x}}{\left(x^2-1\right)^\frac32}=\tan(\theta)+c=\frac{x}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}+c
      </me>.
  </p>
  <problem>
    <idx><h>Drills</h></idx>
    <p>
      Confirm that this is correct by differentiating:
      <m>\frac{x}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}+c</m>.
    </p>
  </problem>

  <p>
    Fortunately, we were still able to handle this, but what if we
    started with the integral:
    <m>\int\frac{x}{\left(x^2-1\right)^\frac32}\dx{x}{}</m>?
  </p>
  <p>
    The substitution <m>x=\sec(\theta)</m> leads to:
    <m>\int{\frac{\sec(\theta)}{\tan^2(\theta)}}\dx{\theta}</m>.
    How do we handle that?
  </p>
  <aside>
    <title>Comment</title>

    <p>
      Confirm this yourself.
    </p>
  </aside>
  <p>
    We rewrite it as
    <me>
      \int{\frac{\sec(\theta)}{\tan^2(\theta)}}\dx{\theta}=\int\frac{1/\cos(\theta)}{\sin^2(\theta)/\cos^2(\theta)}\dx{\theta}=\int\frac{\cos(\theta)}{\sin^2(\theta)}\dx{\theta}=\int\cot(\theta)\csc(\theta)\dx{\theta}=-\csc(\theta)+c
      </me>.
  </p>
  <p>
    This example underscores the need to be able to compute a
    variety of integrals involving trigonometric functions. Again,
    it is a trial and error kind of thing, but there are some
    standard tricks to learn. It is probably best to learn these
    tricks by looking at some specific examples, but as you do,
    focus on the technique being used and how it can be used on
    similar integrals, not the specific example.
  </p>

  <example xml:id="OddSinPower">
    
    <p>
      <me>
        \int\sin^3(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}
      </me>

      Since sine is raised to an odd power, it makes sense to
      <q>save one of the sines</q> and convert everything else to
      cosine, utilizing the Pythagorean identity
      <m>\sin^2(\theta)=1-\cos^2(\theta)</m>, and then apply a
      substitution as follows. First we <q>save a sine.</q>
      <me>
        \int\sin^3(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta} =
        \int\sin(\theta)\sin^2(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}=\int(1-\cos^2(\theta))\cos^2(\theta)\sin(\theta)\dx{\theta}
        </me>.  Next we let <m>z=\cos(\theta)</m>, so that
        <m>\dx{z}=-\sin(\theta)\dx{\theta}</m>, which gives
        <md>
          <mrow>\int\sin^3(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta} \amp =
          \int(1-z^2)z^2(-\dx{z})</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp =\int(z^4-z^2)\dx{z}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp =\frac{z^5}{5}=\frac{z^3}{3}+c</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp
          =\frac{\cos^5(\theta)}{5}=\frac{\cos^3(\theta)}{3}+c</mrow>
          </md>.
    </p>
  </example>
  <exercise>
    

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Had the cosine been raised to an odd power in <xref
        ref="OddSinPower"></xref>, we could have <q>saved
        one of the cosines</q> instead.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute
          <m>\int\sin^2(\theta)\cos^3(\theta)\dx{\theta}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <example>
    <p>
      Notice that in <xref ref="OddSinPower"></xref> there
      would have been nothing wrong with computing
      <m>\int\sin^3(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}</m> as
      follows:
      <md>
        <mrow>           \int\sin^3(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta} \amp{}=
        \int\sin^3(\theta)\cos(\theta)\cos(\theta)\dx{\theta}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp{}=
        \int\sin^3(\theta)\sqrt{1-\sin^2(\theta)}\cos(\theta)\dx{\theta}.</mrow>
      </md>
      It's just that it is not immediately clear how to
      continue from here.  Most people will shy away from this
      because of the square root but in fact, this integral can
      be computed using techniques you already know.
    </p>
    <p>
      First, the elementary substitution <m>x=\sin(\theta)</m> will
      give:
      <me>
        \int\sin^3(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta} = \int
        x^3\sqrt{1-x^2}\dx{x} </me>.
    </p>
    <p>
      You see why we wouldn't want to go this route, right? Recall
      that we introduced trigonometric substitutions precisely so
      we could handle integrals like this last one. It would seem
      to be counterproductive to take this path since we <em>
      started </em> with an integral involving trigonometric
      functions.
    </p>
    <p>
      While our goal is to be able to work out integrals by the
      simplest possible method, not the most difficult, it can
      instructive to see that a computation can be done in more
      than one manner so we will pursue this just a bit farther.
    </p>
  </example>
  <exercise>
    

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Compute the integral <m>\int x^3\sqrt{1-x^2}\dx{x}</m>
        using these substitutions:
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>x=\sin(\theta)</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>u=1-x^2</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <conclusion>
      <p>
        Finish <xref ref="OddSinPower">example</xref> using each of
        the substitutions above. Do you get the same solution as
        before?
      </p>
    </conclusion>
  </exercise>
  <exercise xml:id="SinCosOddPower">
    

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Compute the integral
        <m>\int\sin^3(\theta)\cos^3(\theta)\dx{\theta}</m> by:
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Saving one of the cosines and converting everthing else
          into sines.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Saving one of the sines and converting everthing else
          into cosines.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Do you get the same result in parts (a) and (b)? Explain.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <example xml:id="SinCosEven">
    <p>
      What happens if you don't have an odd power of sine or
      cosine?  For example, suppose you have
      <m>\int\sin^2(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Saving a sine or cosine would lead to an integrand with a
      square root, which we are trying to avoid, if we can help
      it. In this case, there are a couple of trigonometric
      identities that can help. They the Half-Angle formlas:
      <me>
        \sin^2(\theta) = \frac12\left(1-\cos(2\theta)\right) \text{
        and } \cos^2(\theta)=\frac12\left(1+\cos(2\theta)\right)
        </me>.  Using these identities in our integral we see that
        <md>
          <mrow>\int\sin^2(\theta)\cos^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}\amp
          =\frac14\int(1-\cos(2\theta))(1+\cos(2\theta))\dx{\theta}</mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp =\frac14\int (1-\cos^2(2\theta))\dx{\theta}
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
            \amp =\frac{1}{4}\int\sin^2(2\theta)\dx{\theta}
          </mrow>
        </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      Using the Half-Angle formula again we obtain
      <me>
        \frac{1}{4}\int\sin^2(2\theta)\dx{\theta} =
        \frac18\int(1-\cos(4\theta))\dx{\theta} =
        \frac18\left(\theta-\frac14\sin(4\theta)\right)+c
      </me>
    </p>
  </example>
  <problem>
    <idx><h>Drills</h></idx>
    <p>
      Show that we get the same result if we use the Double Angle
      formula: <m>\sin(2\theta)=2\sin(\theta)\cos(\theta)</m>.
    </p>
  </problem>
  <example>
    <p>
      <m>
        \int\sec^4(\theta)\tan^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      In this example, we can save a <m>\sec^2(\theta)</m> as part
      of the differential and use the identity
      <m>\sec^2(\theta)=1+\tan^2(\theta)</m> to change everything
      else into an expression in tangent. Since the secant is to an
      even power this again avoids square roots, which is the
      general idea.
      <md>
        <mrow>\int \sec^4(\theta)\tan^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}\amp
        =\int
        \sec^2(\theta)\tan^2(\theta)\sec^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}</mrow>
        <mrow>
          \int(1+\tan^2(\theta))\tan^2(\theta)\sec^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}
        </mrow>
      </md>
      Letting <m>y=\tan(\theta)</m> we have
      <m>\dx{y}=\sec^2(\theta)\dx{\theta}</m>, so we obtain

      <md>
        <mrow>\int(1+y^2)y^2\dx{y}=\int(y^2+y^4)\dx{y}=\frac{y^3}{3}+\frac{y^5}{5}+c=\frac{\tan^3(\theta)}{3}+\frac{\tan^5(\theta)}{5}+c</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
  </example>

  <example>
    <p>
      If tangent occurs to an odd power, we can save a tangent and
      a secant as part of the differential and use the same
      identity to convert everything else to secant.
      <me>
        \int\sec^2(\theta)\tan^3(\theta)\dx{\theta} =
        \int\sec^2(\theta)\tan^2(\theta)\sec(\theta)\tan(\theta)\dx{\theta{}}=\int\sec^2(\theta)(\sec^2(\theta)-1)\sec(\theta)\tan(\theta)\dx{\theta}
        </me>.  Letting <m>u=\sec(\theta)</m> we have
        <me>
          \int u^2(u^2-1)\dx{u}=\int
          (u^4-u^2)\dx{u}=\frac{u^5}{5}-\frac{u^3}{3}+c=\frac{\sec^5(\theta)}{5}-\frac{\sec^3(\theta)}{3}+c
          </me>.
    </p>
  </example>

  <exercise>
    

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Consider the integral
        <me>
          \int\sec^4(\theta)\tan^3(\theta)\dx{\theta}
        </me>
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute this integral by saving a <m>\sec^2(\theta)</m>
          and converting the rest into an expression in tangent.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute this integral by saving a
          <m>\sec(\theta)\tan(\theta)</m> and converting the rest
          into an expression in secant.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Verify the at you get the same result in (a) and (b).
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    

    <p>
      Previously we computed <m>\int \tan(\theta)\dx{\theta}</m>
      using the identity
      <m>\tan(\theta)=\frac{\cos(\theta)}{\sin(\theta)}</m>. We
      could also use the identity
      <m>\tan(\theta)=\frac{\sec(\theta)\tan(\theta)}{\sec(\theta)}\dx{\theta}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Do we get a different answer? Explain.
    </p>
  </exercise>
  <p>
    The same tricks we applied with secant and tangent would apply
    equally well to integrals involving cosecant and cotangent
    using the identity <m>\csc^2(\theta)=1+\cot^2(\theta)</m>. Of
    course, we have not covered every type of integral that can
    occur and you can always find integrals that will take other
    tricks. We've only provided some basics that you can build on
    as you gain experience. So practice, practice, practice!
  </p>
</subsection>
</section>




<section xml:id="SECTIONPartFrac">
  <title>Back to Logistic Growth: Partial Fractions</title>
  <subsection>
    
    <title>Intro</title>

    <p>
      Recall the <xref ref="EQUATIONLogEq">IVP</xref>.
      <!-- <men xml:id="LogisticGrowthFromDiffCalc"> -->
      <!--   \dfdx{y}{t}=.01y\left(1-\frac{y}{100}\right)=0.0001(100-y) -->
      <!-- </men>.   -->
      In  <xref
      ref="SECTIONpopulation-dynamics"></xref> we analyzed this growth rate to
      draw a qualitative graph of <m>y=y(t)</m>, but we could not
      produce specific values of <m>t</m> for where things
      happened, because we didn't have a formula for
      <m>y(t)</m>. We now have the techniques needed to find
      <m>y(t)</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      First we separate the
      variables:<me>\frac{\dx{y}}{y(100-y)}=0.0001y\dx{t} </me>.
      To integrate the left-hand side, we could expand the
      denominator to complete the square and apply the appropriate
      trigonometric substitution.
    </p>
    <p>
      As we've mentioned before, all mathematical models are
      simplifications of reality, and typically are modified to
      take into account more complexities. For example, consider
      the following modification of the logistic model above
      <me>\dfdx{y}{t}=.01y\left(1-\frac{y}{100}\right)\left(\frac{y}{10}-1\right)=0.00001y(100-y)(y-10)
      </me>

      In this case, <m>10</m> is called the <em>minimum viability
      level of the population.</em> (Why?) Solving this would
      require that we compute the integral <me>\int
      \frac{\dx{y}}{y(100-y)(y-10)}</me>.  This form of this
      integral does not suggest any obvious trigonometric
      substitution so we will need a new idea.
    </p>

    <p>
      <idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>partial fractions</h></idx>
      The next technique is wholly algebraic in nature. The trick
      to try and separate the integrand into <term>partial
      fractions</term> each of which will be easier to integrate
      than the original. For example, consider the expression
      <m>\frac{1}{y(100-y)}</m>. With begin by making a reasonable,
      educated guess that such a fraction can be written as
      <m>\frac{1}{y(100-y)}=\frac{A}{y}+\frac{B}{100-y}</m>, where
      <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are constant to be determined. We can
      see if this guess pans out by combining the partial fractions
      to obtain the original.
      <me>\frac{A}{y}+\frac{B}{100-y}=\frac{A(100-y)+By}{y(100-y)}=\frac{100A+(B-A)y}{y(100-y)}</me>
      Comparing this with <m>\frac{1}{y(100-y)}</m> we see that if
      they are to be equal we must have <m>100A=1</m> and
      <m>B-A=0</m>. Therefore <m>A=B=\frac{1}{100}</m>. Thus
      <me>\frac{1}{y(100-y)}=\frac{1/100}{y}+\frac{1/100}{100-y}</me>. Substituting
      into the original integral we see that
      <md>
        <mrow>
          \int\frac{\dx{y}}{y(100-y)}\amp
        =\int\frac{1/100}{y}\dx{y}+\int\frac{1/100}{100-y}\dx{y}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp
        =\frac{1}{100}\left(\int\frac{\dx{y}}{y}+\int\frac{\dx{y}}{100-y}\right)</mrow>
      </md>
      and so
      <mdn>
        <mrow
            xml:id="PartFrac1">\int\frac{\dx{y}}{y(100-y)}=\frac{1}{100}\left(\ln(y)-\ln(100-y)\right)+C</mrow>
      </mdn>
    </p>
    <aside>
      <title>Comment</title>
      <p>
        This isn't really a guess. There is a theorem from algebra
        that says that there will always be constants <m>A</m> and
        <m>B</m> such that
        <m>\frac{1}{y(100-y)}=\frac{A}{y}+\frac{B}{100-y}</m> but
        since we haven't discussed this yet we'll just roll with it
        for now.
      </p>
    </aside>
    <exercise>
      

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use <xref ref="PartFrac1">equation</xref> to find
            <m>y</m> for the logistic growth model with the initial
            condition <m>y(0)=0</m>
            <me>\dfdx{y}{t}=0.01y\left(1-\frac{y}{100}\right)\hskip5mm
            y(0)=0</me> for the case when <m>y\lt 100</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Solve the same problem for the case where <m>y\gt
            100</m>.
          </p>
          <aside>
            <title>Comment</title>
            <p>
              This is a spot where you need to look at the absolute
              value in the logarithm. We told you it comes up
              occasionally.
            </p>
          </aside>
        </statement>
      </task>

    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="PartialFractionSubsection">
    <title>The Partial Fraction Decomposition</title>
    <p>
      <idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>rational functions</h></idx>
      Now that we've seen that decomposing a ratio of polynomials
      (these are called <term>rational functions</term>) into a sum
      of partial fractions is possible, we'll look for a systematic
      way of doing this for any <term> rational function
      </term>. Our method will hinge on the following theoretical,
      algebraic fact.
    </p>
    <p>
      Suppose we have two polynomials <m>p(x)</m> and <m>q(x)</m>
      which have no common factors (other than constants). Then
      there are polynomials <m>r(x)</m> and <m>s(x)</m> such that
      <me>r(x)\cdot{}p(x)+s(x)\cdot{}q(x)=1</me>.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="ElementaryPartFracDecomp">
      <p>
        For example notice that if <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are
        constants then <m>x+a</m> and <m>x+b</m> have no common
        factors. Since <m>(x+a)-(x+b)=a-b</m> it follows that
        
        <me>\frac{1}{a-b}(x+a)+\frac{-1}{a-b}(x+b)=1</me>.
        
      </p>
      <aside>
        <title>Comment</title>
        <p>
          Notice that since <m>\frac{1}{a-b}</m> and
          <m>\frac{-1}{a-b}</m> are constants they are polynomials
          of degree zero.
        </p>
      </aside>
    </example>
    <p>
      Our approach to the problem in <xref
      ref="ElementaryPartFracDecomp">example</xref> was  somewhat
      ad<ndash/>hoc. We will eventualy need a more systematic approach but
      it will be useful to look at some more examples first. So for
      now we will use an       (educated) guess and check
      method. Notice that in the <xref
      ref="ElementaryPartFracDecomp">example</xref> we had
      <md>
        <mrow>\frac{1}{(x+a)(x+b)}\amp =\frac{\frac{1}{a-b}(x+a)+\frac{-1}{a-b}(x+b)}{(x+a)(x+b)}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{\frac{1}{a-b}}{x+b}+\frac{\frac{-1}{a-b}}{x+a}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp =\frac{\frac{1}{a-b}}{x+b}-\frac{\frac{1}{a-b}}{x+a}
        </mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      It is generally true that if <m>r(x)\cdot p(x+s(x)\cdot
      q(x)=1</m> then
      <me>\frac{1}{p(x)\cdot{}q(x)}=\frac{r(x)\cdot{}p(x)+s(x)\cdot{}q(x)}{p(x)\cdot{}q(x)}=
      \frac{s(x)}{p(x)}+\frac{r(x)}{q(x)}</me>. Multiplying by
      <m>t(x)</m> we have <me>\frac{t(x)}{p(x)\cdot{}q(x)}=
      \frac{t(x)\cdot
      s(x)}{p(x)}+\frac{t(x)\cdot{}r(x)}{q(x)}</me>.  Setting
      <m>A(x)=t(x)\cdot{}s(x)</m> and <m>B(x)=t(x)\cdot r(x)</m>
      gives
      <md>
        <mrow>\frac{t(x)}{p(x)\cdot{}q(x)}=
        \frac{A(x)}{p(x)}+\frac{B(x)}{q(x)}</mrow> </md>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>Partial Fraction Decomposition</h></idx>
      Everything we've just shown assumes that if <m>p(x)</m> and
      <m>q(x)</m> are known then <m>r(x)</m> and <m>s(x)</m> can be
      found so that <m>r(x)\cdot p(x)+ s(x)\cdot q(x)=1</m>. For
      arbitrary functions this is a very restrictive
      condition. However as we observed above, if <m>p(x)</m> and
      <m>q(x)</m> are polynomials having only trivial common
      factors then the existence of <m>r(x)</m> and <m>s(x)</m> is
      guaranteed. Thus for polynomials the <term> Partial Fraction
      Decomposition </term> is also guaranteed.
    </p>
    <aside>
      <title>Mathematical Terminology</title>
      <p>
        The word <q>trivial</q> is very context dependent in
        mathematics. In this context a <q>trivial common factor</q>
        would be a constant. For example, <m>2</m> is a trivial
        common factor of <m>(2x-4)</m> and <m>2x+6</m>.
      </p>
    </aside>


    <p>
      We formalize this in the following theorem.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="PartialFractionDecomp">
      
      <title>The Partial Fraction Decomposition (PFD)</title>
      <p>
        If <m>P(x)</m>, <m>Q(x)</m>, and <m>R(x)</m> are
        polynomials having no non<ndash/>trivial common factors with
        <m>\deg(P)\lt\deg(Q)+ \deg(R)</m> then there exist
        polynomials <m>A(x)</m> and <m>B(x)</m>,
        <m>\deg{A}\lt\deg{Q}</m> and <m>\deg(B)\lt\deg(R)</m>, such
        that <me>\frac{P(x)}{Q(x)\cdot{}R(x)} =
        \frac{A(x)}{Q(x)}+\frac{B(x)}{R(x)}</me>.
      </p>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      As stated in <xref ref="PartialFractionDecomp">Theorem</xref>
      the PFD is very comprehensive. We will
    </p>
    <p>
      To extend this idea further, if <m>p\left(x\right),\
      q\left(x\right),\ r(x)</m> have no nontrivial factors, then
      there are polynomials <m>A\left(x\right),\ B\left(x\right),\
      C(x)</m> with <me>\frac{t(x)}{p\left(x\right)\cdot
      q\left(x\right)\cdot
      r(x)}=\frac{A\left(x\right)}{p\left(x\right)}+\frac{B\left(x\right)}{q\left(x\right)}+\frac{C\left(x\right)}{r\left(x\right)}</me>
      and this can be extended to any number of factors in the
      denominator.  Again, this can be proven theoretically, and
      this partial fractions decomposition can be obtained
      systematically, but we will adopt a guess and check method to
      find <m>A,\ B,\ C</m>.  To make our guess a little more
      educated, the following fact can be employed.  You can make
      peace with this in your own closet.
    </p>
    <p>
      If the degree of <m>t(x)</m> is less than the degree of
      <m>p(x)\cdot q(x)\cdot r(x)</m>, then <m>A,B,C</m> can be
      chosen with <m>\deg( A)\lt \deg(p), \deg(B)\lt \deg(q),
      \deg(C)\lt \deg(r)</m>.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="EXAMPLEPFD1">
      <p>
        
        Recall we had
        <me>\int{\frac{dy}{y\left(100-y\right)(y-10)}}</me>

        To compute this we will find the partial fractions
        decomposition of
        <m>\frac{1}{y\left(100-y\right)\left(y-10\right)}</m>.  We
        make the educated guess
        <me>\frac{1}{y\left(100-y\right)\left(y-10\right)}=\frac{A}{y}+\frac{B}{100-y}+\frac{C}{y-10}</me>
        and determine what <m>A,B,C</m> are.  This can be done in a
        number of ways, but the most direct (and labor intensive)
        way to do this is to combine the terms in the right-hand
        side and compare coefficients.


        <me>\frac{1}{y\left(100-y\right)\left(y-10\right)}=\frac{A\left(100-y\right)\left(y-10\right)+By\left(y-10\right)+Cy\left(100-y\right)}{y\left(100-y\right)\left(y-10\right)}</me>

        <me>=\frac{A\left(-y^2+110y-100\right)+B\left(y^2-10y\right)+C\left(100y-y^2\right)}{y\left(100-y\right)\left(y-10\right)}</me>

        <me>=\frac{\left(-A+B-C\right)y^2+\left(110A-10B+100C\right)y+\left(-1000A\right)}{y\left(100-y\right)\left(y-10\right)}</me>
      </p>

      <p> Since the fractions must be equal and the denominators
      are the same, the numerators must also be equal. Thus

      <md>
        <mrow> -A+B-C&amp; =0</mrow> <mrow>110A-10B+100C&amp;
        =0</mrow> <mrow>-1000A&amp; =1</mrow>
      </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        Solve these equations anyway you wish, but you should get
        <m>A=-\frac{1}{1000}</m>, <m>B=\frac{1}{9000}</m>, and <m>
        C=\frac{1}{900}</m>.
        
        
        Thus
        <me>\frac{1}{y\left(100-y\right)\left(y-10\right)}=\frac{-1/1000}{y}+\frac{1/9000}{100-y}+\frac{1/900}{y-10}</me>
        so


        <me>\int{\frac{dy}{y\left(100-y\right)\left(y-10\right)}}=-\frac{1}{1000}\int{\frac{dy}{y}}+\frac{1}{9000}\int{\frac{dy}{100-y}}+\frac{1}{900}\int{\frac{dy}{y-10}}</me>

        <me>=-\frac{1}{1000}{\mathrm{ln} y\
        }-\frac{1}{9000}{\mathrm{ln} \left(100-y\right)\
        }+\frac{1}{900}{\mathrm{ln} \left(y-10\right)\ }+c</me>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      The PFD is Algebra, not Calculus, but as the problems and
      examples above show it can be very tedious algebra. There are
      shortcuts to the process which can eliminate some of the
      tedium, but the problem with shorcuts is that if you do not
      thoroughly understand the underlying goal it is all too easy
      to mess up the computation. As a rule, you should not start
      using computational shortcuts until you have thoroughly
      mastered the full calculation.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="EXAMPLEHeaviCover">
      <title>Heaviside's Cover-up Method</title>
      <p>Suppose we wish to find the partial fractions
      decomposition of <m>\frac{3x+1}{(x-1)(x-2)(x-5)}</m>.  As
      before, we have <men
      xml:id="EQUATIONHeavisideCover1">\frac{3x+1}{(x-1)(x-2)(x-5)}=\
      \frac{A}{x-1}+\frac{B}{x-2}+\frac{C}{x-5} </men> This leads
      to
      <me>3x+1=A\left(x-2\right)\left(x-5\right)+B\left(x-1\right)\left(x-5\right)+C(x-1)(x-2)</me>
      </p>

      <p>
        Observe that <xref ref="EQUATIONHeavisideCover1"></xref>
        will be true for every real (or complex) value of <m>x</m>.
        The factor <m>x-1</m> appears in two of the terms on the
        right suggests that we let <m>x=1.</m> In that case we have
        <me>3\left(1\right)+1=A\left(1-2\right)\left(1-5\right)</me>
        or
        <me>\frac{3\left(1\right)+1}{\left(1-2\right)\left(1-5\right)}=A.</me>
      </p>

      <aside>
        <title>Comment</title>
        <p>
          Actually we are replacing <m>x-1</m> with 1.
        </p>
      </aside>
      <p>
        We did not simplify this last formula in order to highlight
        the following<m>.</m> Observe that we get the same result
        if we simply <q>cover up</q> the factor <m>(x-1)</m> on the
        left side of <xref ref="EQUATIONHeavisideCover1"></xref>
        above and set <m>x=1.</m>
        <me>A=\frac{3\left(1\right)+1}{(\text{covered})\left(1-2\right)\left(1-5\right)}=1.</me>
      </p>

      <p>
        In precisely the same fashion (setting <m>x=2</m> and
        <m>x=3</m>) we get:
        <me>B=\frac{\left(3\right)2+1}{\left(2-1\right)\left(\text{covered}\right)\left(2-5\right)}=\
        \frac{-7}{3}, </me> and
        <me>C=\frac{\left(3\right)5+1}{(5-1)(5-2)(\text{covered})}=\frac{4}{3},</me>
        so that
        <me>\frac{3x+1}{(x-1)(x-2)(x-5)}=\frac{1}{x-1}+\frac{-7/3}{x-2}+\frac{4/3}{x-5}.\
        </me>
      </p>
      <aside>
        <title>Warning!</title>
        <p>
          In order to use Heaviside<rsq/>s Cover<ndash/>Up Method you must have
          <em>distinct linear</em> factors in the denominator.
          
        </p>
        <p>
          
          In this example they were <m>x-1</m>, <m>x-2</m>, and
          <m>x-5</m>. If our rational function had been
          <me>\frac{3x+1}{(x-1)^2(x-2)(x-5)}</me> Heaviside's
          Method would not work because <m>(x-1)^2</m> is not
          linear.
        </p>
        <p>
          Try it and see what goes wrong.
        </p>
      </aside>

      <p>
        <idx><h>Vocabulary</h><h>Heaviside<rsq/>s Cover-Up Method (HCUM)</h></idx>
        This trick is known as <term>Heaviside<rsq/>s Cover-Up Method
        (HCUM)</term>. It is well known, and can be used to
        find the PFD of a rational function as long as the
        denominator can be factored into distinct linear factors.
      </p>

    </example>
    <p>
      In the previous partial fractions decompositions, we started
      with a rational function where the degree of the numerator
      was less than the degree of the denominator and where the
      factors in the denominator were linear.  In this section, we
      will expand our techniques to encompass other situations.
    </p>
    <p>
      For example, suppose the degree of the numerator is not less
      than the degree of the denominator.  If this is the case,
      then we can perform long division first and then find the
      partial fractions decomposition of the remainder.  For
      example, suppose we have
      <me>\frac{x^3-2x+1}{x^2+x-6}=\frac{x^3-2x+1}{\left(x-2\right)\left(x+3\right)}</me>
      We first perform long division of the original rational
      function.
      <mdn>
        <mrow number="no">\frac{x^3-2x+1}{x^2+x-6}&amp;
        =x-1+\frac{5x-5}{x^2+x-6}</mrow> <mrow
        xml:id="EQUATIONHeaviNotLowest">&amp;=x-1+5\left(\frac{x-1}{\left(x-2\right)\left(x+3\right)}\right)</mrow>
      </mdn>
    </p>
    <p>
      We can now perform a partial fractions decomposition on the
      remaining fraction.
    </p>
    <problem  xml:id="PROBLEM">
      <idx><h>Drills</h></idx>
      <p>
        Use HCUM to complete the decomposition in <xref
        ref="EQUATIONHeaviNotLowest"></xref>.
      </p>
    </problem>

    <example xml:id="EXAMPLEHeaviNonLinear">
      <title>The PFD With Nonlinear Factors in the
      Denominator</title>
      <p>
        What about something like
        <me>\frac{3x+2}{x^2\left(x-1\right)}</me> Since this
        function satisfies all of the conditions of <xref
        ref="PartialFractionDecomp"></xref> we can still decompose
        it into partial fractions. However since <m>x^2</m> is not
        linear we can't use Heaviside's Method.
      </p>
      <p>
        Recall that in the decomposition, the numerators in the
        individual terms can be chosen so that the degrees are less
        than the degrees in the denominators.  This being said, we
        make the following educated guess as to the form of the
        partial fractions decomposition.
        
        <me>\frac{3x+2}{x^2\left(x-1\right)}=\frac{Ax+B}{x^2}+\frac{C}{x-1}</me>
      </p>
      <p>
        We can now recombine this to determine <m>A,B,</m> and
        <m>C</m>.
        <me>\frac{3x+2}{x^2\left(x-1\right)}=\frac{Ax+B}{x^2}+\frac{C}{x-1}=\frac{\left(Ax+B\right)\left(x-1\right)+Cx^2}{x^2\left(x-1\right)}</me>
        <me>=\frac{Ax^2+Bx-Ax-B+Cx^2}{x^2\left(x-1\right)}=\frac{\left(A+C\right)x^2+\left(-A+B\right)x-B}{x^2\left(x-1\right)}</me>
        This leads to <me>A+C=0</me> <me>-A+B=3</me> <me>-B=2</me>
      </p>

      <p>
        Solving this (any way you can) we get <me>A=-5,\ B=-2,\
        C=5</me> so that
        <me>\frac{3x+2}{x^2\left(x-1\right)}=\frac{-5x-2}{x^2}+\frac{5}{x-1}</me>
      </p>
      <p>
        
        If we wanted to integrate this, we would obtain
      </p>
      <p>
        
        <me>\int{\frac{3x+2}{x^2\left(x-1\right)}}\
        \dx{x}=\int{\left(\frac{-5x-2}{x^2}+\frac{5}{x-1}\right)\dx{x}}</me>
        <me>=\int{\left(-\frac{5}{x}-\frac{2}{x^2}+\frac{5}{x-1}\right)\dx{x}}</me>
        <me>=-5{\mathrm{ln} x\ }+2x^{-1}+5{\mathrm{ln}
        \left(x-1\right)\ }+c</me>
      </p>
      <p>
        
        
        Notice in this example that we really needed to look at the
        most general possible polynomial of degree one less than
        the denominators in the partial fractions decomposition; we
        would not have obtained the correct answer otherwise.
      </p>

    </example>

    <aside>
      <title>Comment</title>
      <p>
        This problem shows that we really need to use the most
        general polynomial of degree one less than the denominators
        in the partial fractions decomposition.
      </p>
    </aside>
    <exercise xml:id="EXERCISEHeaviNonLinear">
      

      <statement>
        <p>
          <idx><h>Partial Fraction Decomposition</h></idx> Show
          that if we tried the following decomposition
          <me>\frac{3x+2}{x^2\left(x-1\right)}=\frac{A}{x^2}+\frac{B}{x-1}</me>
          then no values for <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> would satisfy
          this.
        </p>

      </statement>
    </exercise>

    <example xml:id="EXAMPLEPFD2">
      <p>
        Suppose we need to compute
        <me>\int{\frac{25}{{\left(x-2\right)}^2(x^2+1)}}\
        \dx{x}</me> Applying our partial fractions decomposition,
        we get
        
        
        <me>\frac{25}{{\left(x-2\right)}^2\left(x^2+1\right)}=\frac{Ax+B}{{\left(x-2\right)}^2}+\frac{Cx+D}{x^2+1}</me>
        <me>=\frac{\left(Ax+B\right)\left(x^2+1\right)+\left(Cx+D\right){\left(x-2\right)}^2}{{\left(x-2\right)}^2\left(x^2+1\right)}</me>
        <me>=\frac{\left(A+C\right)x^3+\left(B-4C-D\right)x^2+\left(A+4C+4D\right)x+\left(B-4D\right)}{{\left(x-2\right)}^2\left(x^2+1\right)}</me>
      </p>
      <p>
        This leads to the equations
        
        <md>

          <mrow>A+C\amp{}=0</mrow>
          <mrow>B-4C-D\amp{}=0</mrow>
          <mrow>A+4C+4D\amp{}=0</mrow>
          <mrow>B-4D\amp{}=25</mrow>

        </md>


        Solving this (any way you can), we get <m>A=-4</m>,
        <m>B=13</m>, <m>C=4</m>, and <m>D=-3</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Getting back to the integral, we have
        
        
        <me>\int{\frac{25}{{\left(x-2\right)}^2\left(x^2+1\right)}}\
        \dx{x}=\int{\frac{-4x+13}{{\left(x-2\right)}^2}}\dx{x}+\int{\frac{4x-3}{x^2+1}\dx{x}}</me>

        <me>=\int{\frac{-4x+13}{{\left(x-2\right)}^2}}\dx{x}+4\int{\frac{x}{x^2+1}\dx{x}}-3\int{\frac{1}{x^2+1}\dx{x}}</me>
        <me>=\int{\frac{-4x+13}{{\left(x-2\right)}^2}}\dx{x}+2{\mathrm{ln}
        \left(x^2+1\right)\ }-3{\mathrm{arctan} x\ }+c</me>


        Notice that the last two integrals were pretty
        straightforward.  This first integral is more problematic.
        There is a little algebraic trick which will allow us to
        break up that integral even further.
        <me>\int{\frac{-4x+13}{{\left(x-2\right)}^2}}\dx{x}=\int{\frac{-4\left(\left(x-2\right)+2\right)+13}{{\left(x-2\right)}^2}}\dx{x}</me>
        <me>=\int{\frac{-4\left(x-2\right)-8+13}{{\left(x-2\right)}^2}}\dx{x}</me>
        <me>=\int{\frac{-4\left(x-2\right)+5}{{\left(x-2\right)}^2}}\dx{x}</me>
        <me>=-4\int{\frac{1}{x-2}\
        \dx{x}}+5\int{\frac{1}{{\left(x-2\right)}^2}}\dx{x}</me>
        <me>=-4{\mathrm{ln} \left(x-2\right)\
        }-5{\left(x-2\right)}^{-1}</me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Putting this all together, we finally have
        
        
        <me>\int{\frac{25}{{\left(x-2\right)}^2\left(x^2+1\right)}}\
        \dx{x}=-4{\mathrm{ln} \left(x-2\right)\
        }-5{\left(x-2\right)}^{-1}+2{\mathrm{ln}
        \left(x^2+1\right)\ }-3{\mathrm{arctan} x\ }+c</me>


        The trick that we employed above is something you might
        want to remember.  It allows us to take our partial
        fractions decomposition a bit further.  For example, if we
        start with


        <me>\int{\frac{x^3}{{\left(2x^2+1\right)}^2}}\ \dx{x}</me>


        we could rewrite this as


        <md>
          <mrow>\int{\frac{x^3}{{\left(2x^2+1\right)}^2}
          \dx{x}}&amp;=\int{\frac{\frac{1}{2}x\left(2x^2\right)}{{\left(2x^2+1\right)}^2}
          \dx{x}}</mrow>
          <mrow>&amp;=\int{\frac{\frac{1}{2}x\left(2x^2+1-1\right)}{{\left(2x^2+1\right)}^2}
          \dx{x}}</mrow>
          <mrow>&amp;=\frac{1}{2}\int{\frac{x}{2x^2+1}\
          \dx{x}}-\frac{1}{2}\int{\frac{x}{{\left(2x^2+1\right)}^2}}\
          \dx{x} </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        The trick that we employed above is something you might
        want to remember.  It allows us to take our partial
        fractions decomposition a bit further.  For example, if we
        start with
        
        
        <me>\int{\frac{x^3}{{\left(2x^2+1\right)}^2}}\ \dx{x}</me>


        we could rewrite this as
        <md>
          <mrow>\int{\frac{x^3}{{\left(2x^2+1\right)}^2}\
          \dx{x}}&amp;
          =\int{\frac{\frac{1}{2}x\left(2x^2\right)}{{\left(2x^2+1\right)}^2}
          \dx{x}}</mrow> <mrow>&amp;
          =\int{\frac{\frac{1}{2}x\left(2x^2+1-1\right)}{{\left(2x^2+1\right)}^2}
          \dx{x}}</mrow> <mrow>&amp;
          =\frac{1}{2}\int{\frac{x}{2x^2+1}\
          \dx{x}}-\frac{1}{2}\int{\frac{x}{{\left(2x^2+1\right)}^2}}\
          \dx{x} </mrow>
        </md>


      </p>
      <aside>
        <title>Note from Bob</title>
        <p>
          Bud -- at this point, how much of the paper you wrote
          should we put in?  Will putting it in be too much at this
          point?  Should be some practice exercises first?  Should
          it be appendicized?  I'm afraid I've already written too
          much on partial fractions decompositions.  I need your
          fresh view on this.
        </p>
      </aside>

      <p>
        Integrating this would be a matter of utilizing the
        substitution <m>y=2x^2+1</m>.  Of course, this could have
        been done earlier to produce
        
        
        
        <md>
          <mrow>\int{\frac{x^3}{{\left(2x^2+1\right)}^2}}\
          \dx{x}&amp; =\int{\frac{x^2}{{\left(2x^2+1\right)}^2}x\
          \dx{x}}</mrow> <mrow>&amp;
          =\int{\frac{\frac{1}{2}\left(y-1\right)}{y^2}\left(\frac{1}{4}dy\right)}</mrow>
          <mrow>&amp; =\frac{1}{8}\left[\int{\frac{1}{y}\
          dy}-\int{\frac{1}{y^2}\ dy}\right]</mrow>
        </md>

        The point is that you have more tools at your disposal to
        transform integrals you don't know how to do into ones that
        you recognize.

      </p>

      <p>
        
        Before we send you off to practice such integrals, we want to
        present you one more option.  You have probably noticed
        that there is more algebra involved than calculus.  Some of
        it is unavoidable, but there are some shortcuts.  For
        example, finding <m>A,B,C,D</m> in the original partial
        fractions decomposition required solving 4 equations in 4
        unknowns.  Again, this was straightforward, but it turns
        out that there is a shortcut for this similar to the HCUM.
        We will present it here.
      </p>
    </example>


